{"Title": "Optimisation of the dibromomaleimide (DBM) platform for native antibody conjugation by accelerated post-conjugation hydrolysis", "Year": 2017, "Source": "Org. Biomol. Chem.", "Volume": "15", "Issue": 14, "Art.No": null, "PageStart": 2947, "PageEnd": 2952, "CitedBy": 33, "DOI": "10.1039/c7ob00220c", "Link": "https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?partnerID=HzOxMe3b&scp=85016962457&origin=inward", "Abstract": "\u00a9 The Royal Society of Chemistry.Disulfide bridging offers a convenient approach to generate site-selective antibody conjugates from native antibodies. To optimise the reagents available to achieve this strategy, we describe here the use of dibromomaleimides designed to undergo accelerated post-conjugation hydrolysis. Conjugation and hydrolysis, which serve to 'lock' the conjugates as robustly stable maleamic acids, is achieved in just over 1 h. This dramatic acceleration is also shown to infer significant improvements in homogeneity, as demonstrated by mass spectrometry analysis.", "AuthorKeywords": null, "IndexKeywords": ["Antibody conjugate", "Antibody conjugation", "Mass spectrometry analysis", "Optimisations", "Site selective"], "DocumentType": "Journal", "PublicationStage": null, "OpenAccess": 1, "EID": "2-s2.0-85016962457", "SubjectAreas": [["Biochemistry", "BIOC", "1303"], ["Physical and Theoretical Chemistry", "CHEM", "1606"], ["Organic Chemistry", "CHEM", "1605"]], "AuthorData": {"49061340500": {"Name": "Morais M.", "AuthorID": "49061340500", "AffiliationID": "60022148", "AffiliationName": "Department of Chemistry, UCL"}, "26536453900": {"Name": "Nunes J.P.M.", "AuthorID": "26536453900", "AffiliationID": "60022148", "AffiliationName": "Department of Chemistry, UCL"}, "36947932100": {"Name": "Karu K.", "AuthorID": "36947932100", "AffiliationID": "60022148", "AffiliationName": "Department of Chemistry, UCL"}, "57193833641": {"Name": "Forte N.", "AuthorID": "57193833641", "AffiliationID": "60022148", "AffiliationName": "Department of Che